### Disable Origin Check Configuration

Source: https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/blob/canary/docs/content/docs/reference/security.mdx

Disables URL validation against trustedOrigins for callbackURL, redirectTo, errorCallbackURL, and newUserCallbackURL. For backward compatibility, this also disables CSRF protection. This option exposes the application to open redirect vulnerabilities.

```typescript
{
  advanced: {
    disableOriginCheck: true
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Disable CSRF Check Configuration

Source: https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/blob/canary/docs/content/docs/reference/security.mdx

Disables CSRF protection including origin header validation, Fetch Metadata checks, and cross-site navigation blocking. This option should be used with caution as it opens the application to CSRF attacks.

```typescript
{
  advanced: {
    disableCSRFCheck: true
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Basic Trusted Origins in Better Auth

Source: https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/blob/canary/docs/content/docs/reference/security.mdx

This example demonstrates how to configure a static list of trusted origins in Better Auth. These explicitly allowed origins help prevent CSRF attacks and open redirects, ensuring that requests are only accepted from approved domains such as 'https://example.com', 'https://app.example.com', and 'http://localhost:3000'.

```typescript
{
  trustedOrigins: [
    "https://example.com",
    "https://app.example.com",
    "http://localhost:3000"
  ]
}
```

--------------------------------

### Validate Trusted Origins in BetterAuth Plugin Endpoint (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/blob/canary/docs/content/docs/concepts/plugins.mdx

Demonstrates how to use the `isTrustedOrigin()` method available on the auth context within a BetterAuth plugin endpoint to validate URLs against configured trusted origins. This ensures custom endpoints adhere to the same security policies as built-in BetterAuth features, preventing untrusted redirects or resource loading.

```ts
import type { BetterAuthPlugin } from "better-auth";
import { createAuthEndpoint, APIError } from "better-auth/api";
import * as z from "zod"

const myPlugin = () => {
    return {
        id: "my-plugin",
        trustedOrigins: [
            "http://trusted.com"
        ],
        endpoints: {
            getTrustedHelloWorld: createAuthEndpoint("/my-plugin/hello-world", {
                method: "GET",
                query: z.object({
                    url: z.string()
                }),
            }, async (ctx) => {
                // The allowRelativePaths option can be used to either allow or disallow relative paths
                if (!ctx.context.isTrustedOrigin(ctx.query.url, { allowRelativePaths: false })) {
                    throw new APIError("FORBIDDEN", {
                        message: "origin is not trusted."
                    });
                }

                return ctx.json({
                    message: "Hello World"
                })
            })
        }
    } satisfies BetterAuthPlugin
}
```

### Security > CSRF Protection > Origin Validation

Source: https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/blob/canary/docs/content/docs/reference/security.mdx

Each request’s `Origin` header is verified to confirm it comes from your application or another explicitly trusted source. Requests from untrusted origins are rejected. By default, Better Auth trusts the base URL of your app, but you can specify additional trusted origins via the `trustedOrigins` configuration option.

